<paragraph blockId="23.[151,1437,1802,1935]" pageId="23" pageNumber="324">
Most of the haploniscids listed here have been found in the northernmost part of the Atlantic Ocean. 
<taxonomicName box="[151,410,1838,1862]" class="Malacostraca" family="Haploniscidae" genus="Haploniscus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Isopoda" pageId="23" pageNumber="324" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="astraphes" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[151,410,1838,1862]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="324">Haploniscus astraphes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[420,486,1838,1863]" pageId="23" pageNumber="324" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[420,480,1838,1863]" pageId="23" pageNumber="324">n. sp</emphasis>
.
</taxonomicNameLabel>
, however, shows an extensive distribution, from the south side of the Greenland- 
<collectingCountry box="[151,234,1874,1899]" name="Iceland" pageId="23" pageNumber="324">Iceland</collectingCountry>
Ridge to the 
<collectingCountry box="[387,468,1874,1899]" name="Guinea-Bissau" pageId="23" pageNumber="324">Guinea</collectingCountry>
Basin, South Atlantic and the 
<collectingCountry box="[814,897,1874,1899]" name="Angola" pageId="23" pageNumber="324">Angola</collectingCountry>
Basin. Whether these really belong to the same species remains to be evaluated using molecular methods.
</paragraph>
